:"August 1328","1352":"1352","1350":"1350","1284":"1284","1273":"1273","1383":"1383","10 October 1314":"10 October 1314","1337":"1337","1315":"1315","1314":"1314","1303":"1303","about 1303":"about 1303","1332":"1332","1453":"1453","1365":"1365","1310":"1310","1299":"1299","about 1322":"about 1322","about 1297":"about 1297","1317":"1317","1328":"1328","Alnwick, Northumberland, England":"Alnwick, Northumberland, England","Preston, Northumberland, England":"Preston, Northumberland, England","Alnwick Castle, Northumberland, England":"Alnwick Castle, Northumberland, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Percy","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (of Norman origin):","nickname from Old French <i>percehaie</i> ‘pierce hedge’ (Old French <i>percer</i> ‘to pierce, penetrate’ + <i>haie</i> ‘hedge, fence’), perhaps with the sense of someone breaking into an enclosure. <i>Percehaie</i> is the name of one of the sons of the foxes Renart and Hermeline in the medieval French epic <i>Roman de Renart</i>, whose earliest known version is from the 1170s. The surname is older than that, but it may originate in a nickname for the fox as ‘enclosure piercer’, perhaps amounting to ‘chicken thief’.","habitational name from any of several places called Percy in Calvados, Eure, and Manche; William <i>de Perci</i>, the Domesday tenant-in-chief and under-tenant of Hugh, Earl of Chester, came from either Percy-en-Auge (Eure) or Percy (Manche)."],"variants":[{"name":"Piercey","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): variant of   Percy  ."]},{"name":"Piercy","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): variant of   Percy  ."]},{"name":"Pearcey","meanings":["English: variant of   Percy  ."]},{"name":"Peercy","meanings":["English: variant of   Percy  ."]},{"name":"Pearcy","meanings":["English: variant of   Percy  ."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705191,"age":12,"year":"1315","toYear":"1317","julianDay":2201354,"title":"Famine Strikes Europe","description":"A famine caused by cold winters and wet summers across Europe caused millions to die due to starvation. Desperation from hunger caused high levels of crime, stampedes in bread lines in London, infanticide, and even cannibalism throughout Europe.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705192,"age":25,"year":"1328","julianDay":2206102,"title":"First War of Scottish Independence","description":"The First War of Scottish Independence began after England invaded Scotland in 1296. The Treaty of Edinburgh was signed in 1328 which declared peace between the two kingdoms and brought the war to an end.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705193,"age":34,"year":"1337","toYear":"1453","julianDay":2209390,"title":"The Hundred Years' War","description":"The Hundred Years' War between France and England was largely due to the question of legitimate succession to the French crown.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When William de Percy was born about 1303, in Preston, Northumberland, England, his father, Sir Henry de Percy, was 31 and his mother, Eleanor FitzAlan, was 20. He married Margaret about 1322. They were the parents of at least 1 daughter. He died in 1350, in his hometown, at the age of 48."},"et":{"about 1303–1350":"umbes 1303–1350","1299–1352":"1299–1352","1303–1350":"1303–1350","1314–Female":"1314–Surnud","–Male":"Surnud","1310–1365":"1310–1365","1332–1383":"1332–1383","1273–1314":"1273–1314","1284–1328":"1284–1328","August 1328":"august 1328","1352":"1352","1350":"1350","1284":"1284","1273":"1273","1383":"1383","10 October 1314":"10. oktoober 1314","1337":"1337","1315":"1315","1314":"1314","1303":"1303","about 1303":"umbes 1303","1332":"1332","1453":"1453","1365":"1365","1310":"1310","1299":"1299","about 1322":"umbes 1322","about 1297":"umbes 1297","1317":"1317","1328":"1328","Alnwick, Northumberland, England":"Alnwick, Northumberland, England","Preston, Northumberland, England":"Preston, Northumberland, England","Alnwick Castle, Northumberland, England":"Alnwick Castle, Northumberland, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"about 1303–1350":"noin 1303–1350","1299–1352":"1299–1352","1303–1350":"1303–1350","1314–Female":"1314–Kuollut","–Male":"Kuollut","1310–1365":"1310–1365","1332–1383":"1332–1383","1273–1314":"1273–1314","1284–1328":"1284–1328","August 1328":"elokuu 1328","1352":"1352","1350":"1350","1284":"1284","1273":"1273","1383":"1383","10 October 1314":"10. lokakuuta 1314","1337":"1337","1315":"1315","1314":"1314","1303":"1303","about 1303":"noin 1303","1